        <record id="demo_blog_post_1" model="api.blog.post">
            <field name="title">Getting Started with REST APIs</field>
            <field name="content"><![CDATA[
                <h2>Introduction to REST APIs</h2>
                <p>REST (Representational State Transfer) is an architectural style for building web services. In this post, we'll explore the fundamentals of REST APIs and how to build them.</p>

                <h3>Key Principles</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Stateless:</strong> Each request contains all information needed</li>
                    <li><strong>Client-Server:</strong> Separation of concerns</li>
                    <li><strong>Cacheable:</strong> Responses can be cached</li>
                    <li><strong>Uniform Interface:</strong> Standardized communication</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>HTTP Methods</h3>
                <p>REST APIs use standard HTTP methods:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li>GET - Retrieve resources</li>
                    <li>POST - Create new resources</li>
                    <li>PUT - Update existing resources</li>
                    <li>DELETE - Remove resources</li>
                </ul>

                <p>Understanding these principles is essential for building effective APIs!</p>
            ]]></field>
            <field name="status">published</field>
            <field name="is_featured" eval="True"/>
            <field name="tags">rest,api,tutorial,beginner</field>
            <field name="author_id" ref="base.user_admin"/>
        </record>

        <record id="demo_blog_post_2" model="api.blog.post">
            <field name="title">Building Your First API with Odoo</field>
            <field name="content"><![CDATA[
                <h2>Create APIs in Odoo</h2>
                <p>Odoo provides a powerful framework for building REST APIs. Let's see how easy it is!</p>

                <h3>Step 1: Create a Controller</h3>
                <pre><code>
from odoo import http
from odoo.http import request

class MyApiController(http.Controller):
    @http.route('/api/hello', type='http', auth='public')
    def hello_world(self):
        return "Hello, API!"
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Step 2: Handle JSON Responses</h3>
                <pre><code>
@http.route('/api/data', type='json', auth='public')
def get_data(self):
    return {'message': 'Hello from JSON API'}
                </code></pre>

                <p>That's it! You've created your first API endpoint in Odoo.</p>
            ]]></field>
            <field name="status">published</field>
            <field name="is_featured" eval="True"/>
            <field name="tags">odoo,api,python,tutorial</field>
            <field name="author_id" ref="base.user_admin"/>
        </record>

        <record id="demo_blog_post_3" model="api.blog.post">
            <field name="title">Understanding Database Models and ORM</field>
            <field name="content"><![CDATA[
                <h2>Working with Odoo ORM</h2>
                <p>The ORM (Object-Relational Mapping) in Odoo makes database operations simple and pythonic.</p>

                <h3>Creating Records</h3>
                <pre><code>
# Create a new record
post = request.env['api.blog.post'].create({
    'title': 'New Post',
    'content': 'Content here'
})
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Reading Records</h3>
                <pre><code>
# Search for records
posts = request.env['api.blog.post'].search([
    ('status', '=', 'published')
])

# Get specific record
post = request.env['api.blog.post'].browse(1)
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Updating Records</h3>
                <pre><code>
post.write({
    'status': 'published'
})
                </code></pre>

                <h3>Deleting Records</h3>
                <pre><code>
post.unlink()
                </code></pre>
            ]]></field>
            <field name="status">published</field>
            <field name="tags">odoo,orm,database,tutorial</field>
            <field name="author_id" ref="base.user_admin"/>
        </record>

        <record id="demo_blog_post_4" model="api.blog.post">
            <field name="title">API Authentication Best Practices</field>
            <field name="content"><![CDATA[
                <h2>Securing Your APIs</h2>
                <p>Authentication is crucial for protecting your API endpoints.</p>

                <h3>Authentication Types in Odoo</h3>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>auth='public':</strong> No authentication required</li>
                    <li><strong>auth='user':</strong> Requires logged-in user</li>
                    <li><strong>auth='none':</strong> No database connection</li>
                </ul>

                <h3>Best Practices</h3>
                <ol>
                    <li>Always use HTTPS in production</li>
                    <li>Implement rate limiting</li>
                    <li>Validate all input data</li>
                    <li>Return appropriate error messages</li>
                    <li>Log authentication failures</li>
                </ol>
            ]]></field>
            <field name="status">draft</field>
            <field name="tags">security,authentication,api,best-practices</field>
